segments.text: their wartime experiences as the high point in their life.
But if you're a professional soldier, which I was, that's just going to work in the morning.
It's not pleasant.
I remember the bad things about it.
People dying.
A young sergeant died in my arms one time.
He got shot.
A couple of my boys got their legs blown off when they stepped on mines.
Had a crazy captain buddy of mine shot his own thumb off.
But, you remember those things, but that's, that's not, you're who you are before you go over there, and I certainly was, and the war didn't change me.
My experiences in combat didn't change me.
I think, like I said, I think being a daddy had more impact on my life.
I learned more about and changed my outlook on life more.
when I had kids than the war did.
Certainly not my death, but I'm not going to be thinking about Vietnam.
I'm going to be thinking about my family.
What are your thoughts about the anti-war protesters?
Well, do you really want to know?
I really want to know.
I think they're a bunch of traitors.
I think people who are honestly against the war have a right to put forth their opinion, but I think some of these
people that call themselves anti-war protesters, nothing more than sympathizes with the enemy.
They're the betrayal of their own countrymen and the role they're fighting.
Jane Fonda's a classic.
Is that why you don't like her?
I don't like her.
I don't like her at all.
I don't like what she did, and I don't like what she's doing today in 1988 to try to make amends for.
Because those boys over there said, how could she do that?
How could she get away with it?
She goes to North Vietnam and pats those guys on the head telling them what a great job she's doing.
You know, they're doing.
And those people and their buddies are killing Americans.
Now, if she is so against America, why doesn't she go to North Vietnam and become a North Vietnamese film star now?
She'd like a life in America.
Yeah, sure, she's making some bucks and she's selling these little exercise tapes and all this crap.
And I understand her career ain't going too well.
And of course, those guys never forget somebody's been betrayed them like that.
And she's been kind of a, she's the head of the temple, if you will.
She's the most visible of them all.
But if this had been World War II, that woman would have been tried and convicted and probably sentenced to death for what she did.
That's terrible what she did.
She went over there and encouraged those people to kill Americans.
And she murdered herself.
She said it in the name of anti-war processing.
Bullshit.
That wasn't anti-war processing.
She was going there and giving aid and encouragement to the enemy.
That's wrong.
She shouldn't have done that.
You know, this is the day of no absolutes, right?
Everything is gray, but what she did was definitely black.
Very, very bad.
She shouldn't have done that.
And what about the kids and the college kids and even the grownups who just protested in the streets?
Well, you know, those people got to write their voice, their opinion.
And... Did you resent them because you gave part of your life, a year of your life to the effort?
No, I didn't give...
I don't resent...
I didn't resent that if...
I would have resented it if I was there against my will, but I went there willingly.
Because...
Would I resent that?
Did I resent it?
I don't think I resent it.
I was disappointed in the fact that all of the American people didn't get behind us while we went over there and put our meat on the line.
And we're out there serving the country.
That means all the Americans.
We're out there performing our public service.
kind of like a fireman goes to a fire and some people are protesting the fact that he's trying to put the fire out.
Can you relate to that?
Okay, we were going out there, we thought we were doing the right thing.
Our government told us we were doing the right thing.
The civilians that we worked for were telling us that we were doing the right thing.
Some civilians said, you know, you're terrible and they just didn't say what you,
what you're doing is wrong, they try to make us some kind of monsters, you know, baby killers and all kinds of stuff.
Do you regret your involvement in the war?
No.
Because at that time, I was participating in the tribulations of my time.
I think it was some great philosopher once said, a man who does not participate in the tribulations and triumphs of his time can be accused of not having lived
period of time.
I'm glad I was there and participated in it.
That was my job.
That was what I signed on to do.
That was my responsibility.
That was my task, if you will.
That was what I was doing then.
I was a soldier, and if I had not been there, I would have missed it.
I would have not been doing my job.
Okay.
How do you feel about the draft dodgers, or the people who, well, the people who went to Canada, or the people who
faked ailments or tried to get out of it or tried to join the National Guard?
Well, you know, a lot of guys my age are lawyers and dentists and doctors and have PhDs and stuff and if there had been no war in Vietnam, most of those guys would have never gone on to college.
So, you say people who avoided participating in a war
Some went to Canada, some went to graduate school.
A man's got to follow his own conscience.
That's the beauty of America.
We let you get away with it.
You follow your own conscience.
You do what your conscience says, even in the face of censure by your peer group.
But I tell you what, I was in the 3rd Battalion, 22nd Infantry for a few weeks, and we got in a hell of a combat situation.
I got to know a Spec 5 medic
And I stood there while they pinned the Distinguished Service Cross on that guy's chest.
There's only one greater award that you can get and that's the Medal of Honor.
This guy had crawled out in the fire in combat to rescue wounded GIs.
Medics do that all the time.
He just did it well and he did it a lot of times.
So they gave him the Distinguished Servant's Cross.
Now that's a pretty impressive award.
What makes it even more impressive is this guy was a conscientious objector.
He never carried a weapon.
But yet he still felt obligated to serve his country.
What he always told me was he could never be a conscientious objector in any other country.
I wouldn't let him do it.
but this country was so great and so tolerant that they would let him.
He felt he owed that country something, but while he couldn't in all good conscience bear arms against another human being, he'd go out there and try to save and help American lives and he did that.
He did.
Now, I feel more strongly towards that conscientious objector who at least went to help his fellow
American than the conscientious objector who abandoned his country and went to Canada and only came back when it was safe.
Do you understand the difference?
Did you ever feel that the war should end?
Did you ever feel that Americans should pull out?
Yeah, after we won it.
the 70s, early 70s, in the beginning of the 70s.
Did you agree with the pullout?
Well, you're asking a professional soldier to make political judgments.
I couldn't really do it.
I left the Army.
After Vietnam, it was a drawdown.
They didn't need as many people in the Army.
They had a million and a half people.
Congress mandated that the Army be reduced by 50%.
There's issues for them, so I was released.
They called it a reduction of 40.
How did that make you feel when they discharged you?
That was more traumatic than combat, I want to tell you, because I had to reorient my whole life.
I was 33 years old.
I had to find a new career.
Did you feel resentment then towards the Army?
No, not towards the Army.
Like they had used you?
No, no, not towards the Army at all.
No resentment towards the Army.
I love the Army today.
I still love the Army.
And every day I still draw upon those things which I learned in the Army.
Every day.
My resentment was towards the Congress, because they mandated that the military be reduced, and I lost my job.
Just like a layoff for General Motors.
But that's okay, because in the Army I learned to be resilient and to adjust to change.
So I took my GI Bill, which I earned and I went to college and to law school and then became a lawyer.
How did you, when America decided to pull out, did you feel that that was right?
Yeah, at that time it was because the American people had lost the will to wage war.
Nope, that was a good decision.
You know why?
Why?
There's no point in engaging in a war
Because the American people are not committed to it.
You're just wasting lives.
So, no, it's like gambling.
When you're on a losing streak, you don't throw more money on the table.
I hope they catch it back.
The American people don't want to fight a war no more.
Fine, let's pull the boys out of there and bring them home.
That's a good decision.
Okay.
How did you feel?
Did you watch on TV when the North Vietnamese took over Saigon?
Mm-hmm.
How did you feel then?
I wasn't surprised.
Were you sad?
No.
They were filling a vacuum that we left.
The South Vietnamese had no ability to maintain a war like we were.
Remember, the North Vietnamese never gained control of that country until after the last American left.
In our class, we heard about a man whose

got permission from both governments, the Vietnamese government and the United States government, and they're planning trips, like groups of 12 veterans to go back to Vietnam to help build the country back, build schools and hospitals.
Do you have any desire to do that?
No.
Okay.
Is there any reason?
Take those 12 veterans and send them to Appalachia.
Send them to an Indian reservation.
We'll send them to a ghetto in South Bronx.
I mean, take care of your own first and then go over there and fool around with those people.
I mean, they're doing that for their own edification, not for those people.
If they're so concerned about helping humanity, there's plenty of it right in their own backyard and they go 10,000 miles away.
Do you have any desire to ever go back there?
I just did.
You mean to Vietnam, though?
I just did.
You went to Thailand.
Yeah, that's right next door, and I flew over Saigon.
How did that feel?
It was interesting.
No, no, I forgot how beautiful that part of the world is.
Really gorgeous.

You know, it's funny, when I already owned Vietnam, even in the middle of firefights and bombs going off and people dying, I would say to a couple of buddies of mine, I'd say, you know, this is one hell of a beautiful country.
If there wasn't a war going on, maybe, just maybe, this could be the vacation capital of the world.
Gorgeous beaches, beautiful mountain ranges, and everything's so green and so lush.
And the Vietnamese people are really sweet, darling people.
Tough, hardworking, very cultured, very proud of their country, very nationalistic.
Smart, creative, charming, well-mannered, and that's both sides, north and south.
It's all the same culture.
And I've often thought that, but for all the screwing around politicians, which is what that war was, what a wonderful place it would be to visit.
Yeah, I think you once told me about a trip over there that your school was going to participate in as a sponsor.
I'd rather wait until maybe things are more settled, but yeah, it's a beautiful country.
It's gorgeous.
Pearl of the Orient.
Back to something you just said.
You said that the people were sweet and kind.
There was a tendency for some soldiers to look at them as less than human, as monsters, gooks, you called them, you used to call them.
Did you ever feel like that?
Oh, gooks, slopes, slant eyes, chinks, dinks, you name it.
Sure.
Just like we call the Japanese Japs, yellow bastards.
The Germans will call Kraut or the Bosch.
You always characterize your enemy in derogatory terms.
But some of the best Americans we have today are the Vietnamese who have come here from Vietnam.
So you have nothing against Vietnamese people?
Oh, no.
They're wonderful people.
Even the North ones.
They were fighting for what they believed in, and they fought very hard, and a very, very great sacrifice.
And they were soldiers.
a hell of a good soldier to put up with the enormous losses that they did.
Because every time they came up against us, they lost and they got really hurt bad, but they kept on coming.
You respect that as a professional and another professional.
Tough people, good people.
Opportunists like Jane Fonda, you can never really appreciate because they just take advantage of the situation for their own ends.
But no, I have a,
Tremendous respect for the Vietnamese people.
Wonderful people.
Want to qualify one point?
Okay.
Some of the best Americans we have here today are the Vietnamese Americans.
Hardworking, diligent, loyal to their family and to the community and to the country.
And they did that all after landing here with nothing in their pockets and not even know how to speak Latin.
What do you feel about the memorial that was put up in Washington, D.C.?
Good.
By damn time.
Do you think...
I'd like to go see it.
Some people have objections to it being black and so down to the ground and kind of out of the way.
That's the most significant memorial in Washington, D.C. right now.
More people go to that than anything else.
At least that's what the people on the television told me, isn't it?
More people go there than go to the Washington Monument.
Jefferson Memorial, Lincoln Memorial.
Yeah, that's appropriate then.
You know why?
Because you can go up and touch the names of the men that served there.
It's not just a silly statue or some piece of rock sticking out of the sky.
It's real.

What that is, is the sacrifice of 50,000, the ultimate sacrifice, 50,000 people who truly loved their country and felt that what they were doing was the correct thing and when an American goes up there and sees it and touches it, then he's finally paying tribute to the American men and women who served their country
well, affectionately, served their country with love and affection for their country, who served their country honorably, and gave the ultimate gift to their country and their lives.
Yeah, that's a marvelous memorial.
I look forward to some time going there, maybe with my grandchildren.
And tipping my hat to my comrades in arms who didn't have the chance to continue their lives after their Vietnam service.
You know, I find it really hilarious sometimes when I talk to a list of civilians, people who have never served in the military, never been in any kind of a situation.
I find it hilarious when they talk about their broken shoelaces and the fact that they just can't find the refrigerator that works well or how they had a blowout on their car or some other thing.
The only true thing I ever saw in a movie, Platoon, I think it was, a soldier was heading home and he says, well, after Vietnam, the rest of my life is going to be easy.
That's true.

After participating in a war that had very little popular support, not having your sacrifices and the sacrifices of your peers recognized, after almost getting killed half of the time, the rest of your life seemed pretty simple, uncomplicated.
And I think the vast majority of Vietnam veterans who
or women around this country today realize that.
And they're probably not getting a whole lot of media attention, but those experiences and those things which they learned about themselves during that conflict are enriching their lives right now.
No war is ever without some benefit somewhere along the line.
Vietnam is still different.
Any more questions?
No, I don't think so.
Thank you.
You're welcome.
